    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are attachment styles?</summary>
        <p>Attachment styles are patterns of relating to others that develop in early childhood based on interactions with primary caregivers. The four main styles are Secure (comfortable with closeness and independence), Anxious (craves closeness but fears abandonment), Avoidant (values independence and is uncomfortable with intimacy), and Fearful-Avoidant (wants closeness but is also terrified of it). Your style influences how you bond, handle conflict, and experience intimacy in adult relationships. <a href="/test/attachment-style-quiz/">Take our free Attachment Style Quiz</a> to identify your pattern.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can your attachment style change?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Through a process called earned secure attachment, people with insecure styles can develop secure attachment over time. The most effective pathways include therapy (especially attachment-focused approaches), being in a relationship with a securely attached partner, self-education about attachment theory, and mindfulness practices. Research shows that approximately 25 percent of people's attachment styles change over a four-year period, and the change is almost always in the direction of greater security.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What causes anxious attachment?</summary>
        <p>Anxious attachment typically develops when a child's primary caregiver was inconsistently responsive. Sometimes the caregiver was warm and attentive, and other times they were distracted, unavailable, or preoccupied. This inconsistency teaches the child that love is available but unreliable, creating hypervigilance about the relationship and escalating emotional signals to maintain connection. In adulthood, this translates into a chronic fear of abandonment, reassurance-seeking behavior, and difficulty tolerating uncertainty in relationships.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do avoidant and anxious attachment interact?</summary>
        <p>Anxious and avoidant partners often attract each other in a dynamic called the anxious-avoidant trap. The anxious partner's need for closeness triggers the avoidant partner's need for space, and the avoidant's withdrawal triggers the anxious partner's fear of abandonment. This creates a self-reinforcing push-pull cycle. Breaking it requires both partners to recognize the pattern, communicate openly about their attachment needs, and make conscious efforts to move toward secure behaviors such as self-soothing (for the anxious partner) and staying present (for the avoidant partner).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What percentage of people have secure attachment?</summary>
        <p>Research estimates that approximately 50 to 60 percent of adults have a predominantly secure attachment style. About 20 to 25 percent have an anxious style, 20 to 25 percent have an avoidant style, and roughly 5 percent have a fearful-avoidant (disorganized) style. These percentages vary across cultures and individual studies, but secure attachment is consistently the most common style. The fact that it is the majority pattern suggests that the human capacity for secure bonding is robust, even in imperfect conditions.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

